# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cocoa-appkit-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/appkit] AppKit comprises a collection of Objective-C classes and protocols that can be used to build an application in OpenStep/Cocoa.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/appkit] These classes can also be used in Swift through its Objective-C bridge.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/appkit] Xcode has built-in functionality for developing a Cocoa application using AppKit, including the ability to visually design user interfaces with Interface Builder.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/appkit] It relies heavily on patterns like reference types, delegation, notifications, target–action, and model–view–controller.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/appkit] A sign of the NeXTSTEP heritage, AppKit's classes and protocols still use the "NS" prefix.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/appkit] Most of the applications bundled with macOS—for example, the Finder, TextEdit, Calendar, and Preview—use AppKit to provide their user interface.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/appkit] macOS, iOS, iPadOS, and tvOS also support other UI frameworks, including UIKit, which is derived from AppKit and uses many similar structures, and SwiftUI, a Swift-only declarative UI framework.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/appkit] Prior to macOS Catalina, macOS also supported Carbon, a UI framework derived from the Macintosh Toolbox.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Aqua was introduced at the 2000 Macworld conference in San Francisco.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] It was first released in July with iMovie 2, and with Mac OS X 10.0 the following year.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Aqua is the successor to Platinum, which was used in Mac OS 8, Mac OS 9, and developer releases of Rhapsody (including Mac OS X Server 1.0).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Apple continually revised Aqua with subsequent operating system revisions, including adding SwiftUI design standards and Swift language support into Aqua’s interface, and implementing its design into newer products such as the iPhone.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In 2013, Apple heavily revised the skeuomorphic user interface to adopt a flat design.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In 2025, Apple introduced the Liquid Glass design language across their operating systems.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] For years, Apple had been trying and failing to produce a next-generation Mac OS operating system, including projects code-named Pink, Taligent, and Copland.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X was ultimately built on NeXTSTEP, after Apple purchased NeXT and its CEO, Steve Jobs, returned to Apple, the company he had cofounded.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Early versions of Mac OS X, called Rhapsody, was a developer release that had an interim user interface, blending MacOS 8's "Platinum" and OpenStep looks.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The Rhapsody approach was ultimately abandoned, and the new operating system was dubbed Mac OS X in 1998.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Early developer previews of Mac OS X shipped with an interface similar to Rhapsody, combining classic Mac OS and NextStep.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The final operating system interface, Aqua, would be unveiled at Macworld Expo in January 2000.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Aqua uses blue, white, and gray as the principal colors throughout its style.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Window toolbars, window backgrounds, buttons, menus and other interface elements are all found in either of these colors.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] For instance, toolbars and sidebars are often grey or metal-colored, window backgrounds and popup menus are white and buttons (in older systems also scrollbar handles) are accented with a bright blue.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In versions of OS X prior to OS X Yosemite, most controls have a "glass" or "gel" effect applied to them.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] David Pogue described this effect as "lickable globs of Crest Berrylicious Toothpaste Gel".
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] macOS has few native customization options to change the overall look of the system.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Users can choose a graphite appearance instead of the default blue one.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] When using the graphite appearance, controls have a slate-like, grey-blue or grey color, including the primary window controls which are red, yellow and green with the default appearance.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The appearance option was added at the behest of developers and users who found the blue appearance garish or unprofessional.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] OS X Yosemite added a dark mode that darkens the predominantly white menubar and Dock.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Users can also freely choose a highlight color for text and file selection.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Historically, Aqua had two window designs: the default Aqua windows and "brushed metal" windows.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Aqua windows typically have a metal-like or gray titlebar with three buttons on the left side (for closing, minimizing and zooming or entering fullscreen mode).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Visually, these buttons used to be placed on top, but later appeared 'sunken' into the window.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Aqua windows have almost no frame or outside border, instead drop shadows are used to separate and distinguish active from inactive windows.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The aesthetic of the window backgrounds changed from pin-striped to white backgrounds.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Brushed-metal windows had a thick frame with a metallic texture or dark-gray background and sunken buttons and inner frames.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] They had the additional property of being draggable at every point of the frame instead of just the titlebar and toolbar.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Brushed-metal windows have been largely phased out since Leopard and become visually indistinctive from Aqua windows.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In addition to titlebars, windows can also have toolbars with separate buttons.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Up to Leopard, toolbars were visually separated from the titlebar and had the same background as the window frame or were pin-striped.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Leopard introduced a unified style that extended the metal-like background of the titlebar to the toolbar, making it appear as one whole.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Optionally, a separator could be placed between the titlebar and the toolbar to mimic the previous style.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] OS X Yosemite brought a more-compact version of the toolbar that fused the titlebar and toolbar together, made it shorter and removed the window title (for example, in Safari 8 and later).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Drawers are accessory sidebar views that can slide out from any edge of a window except the top edge.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] They can be resized perpendicular to their window edge but follow the window's size in the other direction.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Drawers were once frequently used to display controls and information that did not need to be always visible, but Apple now recommends against their use.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Sheets are dialog boxes that are modal to a specific window.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] When opened, they are thrust towards the user like a sheet of paper, hence the name.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] They are partially transparent and focus attention on the content of the sheet.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The parent window's controls are disabled until the sheet is dismissed, but the user is able to continue work in other windows (including those in the same application) while the sheet is open.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Menus are backed with a slightly translucent solid gray, and when menu items are highlighted they appear blue.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In application menus, which run in a single bar across the top of the screen, keyboard shortcuts appear to the right-hand side of the menu whilst the actual menu item is on the left.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In Yosemite, the menus are much more translucent and have a blur effect.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Drop down menus for use in windows themselves are also available in several varieties.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The standard "pop up" menu is white with a blue end cap with opposing arrows, whilst 'pull down' menus only have one downward facing arrow in the end cap.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] 'Pull down' menus are available in four different Aqua varieties, most of which have fallen into disuse in later macOS releases.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Text boxes are black on white text with a sunken effect border.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In addition to regular square text boxes, rounded search text boxes are available .
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] For more extensive text requirements, there is also a multi-line text field.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] A combined text box and pull down menu is available, which allows the user to type in a value in addition to choosing from a menu.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] There is also a combination textbox and picker control, which allows the user to type in a date and time or edit it with directional buttons.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X 10.4 introduced a new interface element that allows the user to drag non-editable 'tokens' to a text box, between which text can be typed.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Whitespace before and after the tokens is trimmed.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Standard push buttons with rounded corners are available in two varieties: white and blue.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] A blue button is the default action, and in OS releases prior to Yosemite, would appear to pulse to prompt the user to carry out that action.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The action of a blue button can usually also be invoked with the return key.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] White buttons are usually associated with all other actions.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Also available are rounded bevel buttons, designed to hold an icon; standard square buttons; glass square buttons and round buttons.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In addition, circular, purple online help buttons are available which display help relative to the current task when clicked.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Disclosure triangles, although technically buttons, allow views of controls to be shown and hidden to preserve space.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In macOS, empty check boxes are small, white rounded rectangles.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] When they are checked, they turn blue and a checkmark is present.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] They are essentially buttons which can be toggled on or off.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Radio buttons are similar in appearance and behaviour except that they are circular and contain a dot instead of a check.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Radio buttons are classed into groups of which only one can be activated at a time.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In Yosemite, a short animation was added to show the checkbox or radio button filling in.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] All table views can use alternating blue and white row backgrounds.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Two main types of loading/saving progress indicator are available: a progress bar or a monochromatic spinning wheel (not the spinning pinwheel).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The progress bar itself is available in two varieties: indeterminate, which simply shows diagonal blue and white stripes in animation with no measure of progress; or determinate, which shows a blue pulsing bar against a white background proportional to the percentage of a task completed.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The spinning wheel indicator, also found in the Mac OS X startup screen since version 10.2, is simply a series of 12 increasingly darker grey lines arranged circularly, like the side view of a spoked wheel rotating clockwise.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Many other interfaces have adopted this device, including the Firefox and Camino web browsers and many Web 2.0-influenced web sites.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In Yosemite, the progress bar was changed to a thin, light gray.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The "indeterminate" variation kept the pulses, but slower and spaced out.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] A progress indicator now appears during boot, replacing the spinning wheel indicator found in earlier versions.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Sliders are available in three types: one with tick marks and a triangular scrubber, one with a round scrubber and no tick marks and a circular slider which can be rotated.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] All are available horizontally or vertically.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The circular slider is simply a gray dot on a white circle which can be rotated to set values.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] macOS has a standard control for picking colors which appears as a regular square button with a color sample in the middle.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] When clicked, it shows the standard macOS color palette.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Tabs in macOS are nearly identical to push buttons, with the unselected tab(s) being white and the selected tab being blue.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Image "wells" are also available: a small, sunken container into which image files can be dropped.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] When the well contains an image, it can display a thumbnail representation of the file's contents.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Apple used Lucida Grande as the system typeface from the first release Cheetah to Mavericks.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Occasionally, Apple also used Helvetica and Helvetica Neue, such as in applications like Mail and iPhoto.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Many of these effects can be turned off by the user or are only available on supported hardware.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Aqua is powered by the display server Quartz Compositor.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The Panther version of the Aqua interface shows several changes, most notably brushed metal.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Jobs introduced the Aqua interface as an attempt by Apple to create a more powerful interface for professional users, while making an approachable product for new computer users.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X 10.2 "Jaguar" brought flatter interface elements, such as new buttons and drop-down menus, and reduced the transparency to tone down the pinstripes in windows and menus.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] These trends continued in subsequent Mac OS X releases.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In Mac OS X Panther buttons were made to appear sunken into their surroundings, following a general trend of more flattened interface elements in the operating system.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The traditional pinstripes were replaced with a much subtler theme, most notably in the menu bar, and the use of transparency was again reduced (for example in the title bars of inactive windows).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Tabs also changed; they were made flatter and the whole tab area was sunken rather than raised.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Tab buttons were centered on the top border of the tab area.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] New icons appeared across the system, including a new flatter, glossier Finder icon and a new System Preferences icon.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Panther also featured an increased use of the "Brushed Metal" look, especially to the Finder and Safari web browser.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Brushed Metal had first appeared in QuickTime Player 4.0 in 1999.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Apple's Human Interface Guidelines stated that the brushed metal interface be used for programs that mimic the operation or interface of common real world devices (skeuomorphism).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X Tiger brought more subtle changes, including the unified titlebar scheme.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Pinstripes were removed from the menu bar entirely and replaced with a glossy, white look.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Tabs were altered to appear as normal segmented buttons.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The Apple menu icon was toned down to a more matte appearance and the new Spotlight search utility was permanently bound to the very right of the menu bar in the same color and gradient of the Apple menu.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X Leopard brought wide-ranging changes to Aqua.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The Dock's design, when placed on the left or right side, changed to a black translucent background with a white border and rounded corners.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Context menus had slightly-rounded corners and numerous icons were redesigned, including folder icons and System Preferences icons.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X Snow Leopard made almost no changes to Aqua.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Most notably, the context menu of Dock items changed from a solid white to a translucent black.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X Lion introduced many changes inspired by iOS that persisted in OS X Mavericks as well as OS X Yosemite, although the latter changed the overall aesthetic.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Scrollbars were removed and scrollbar handles turned into thin, semi-transparent bars that disappear when not used.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The corner radii of push buttons were reduced, giving an appearance similar to Mac OS 8 and 9.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The gel-like appearance of most components was replaced with a slightly glossy and flatter look.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Window backgrounds became slightly brighter and window corners were rounded.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] OS X Mountain Lion brought only minor changes and changed the Dock's appearance into a frosted-glass style, with rounded corners, rectangular indicator lights, a new diagonal separator and a new Trash icon.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] OS X Mavericks dispensed with several rich and ornamental designs, reflecting the design overhaul in iOS 7.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The applications Calendar, Contacts, and Notes respectively lost their leather, book, and notepad skeuomorphic appearance (all introduced in Lion).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Linen textures in Notification Center and Launchpad were removed as well and replaced with simple gray backgrounds.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The Dock was made to appear white when set to pop up sideways, somewhat akin to its original design when at such, albeit with the overall design retained from previous skeuomorphic versions.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In OS X Yosemite, many of the Aqua elements and icons were simplified and flattened, following a similar design change in iOS 7.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Apple incorporated the same saturated frosted-glass effect, called "Vibrancy", across the system.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Examples include the Dock, the menubar, sidebars, Notification Center and Mission Control.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] A similar effect was applied to toolbars, but they maintained their gray appearance.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Toolbar buttons became white and Apple introduced a more compact type of toolbar that removed the window title, but retained the toolbar buttons (for example, in Safari).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Certain controls, such as checkboxes and radio buttons, gained animations, whereas animations in other places were removed, such as the "poof" animation when removing an icon from the Dock and the "cube" animation when fast-switching to another user account.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Apple changed the system typeface to Helvetica Neue.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Yosemite also added a "dark theme" that can be enabled by the user in the settings which makes the dock and menu bar black.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] OS X El Capitan made only minor changes to Aqua.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The white toolbar buttons regained a slightly glossy look, the spinning pinwheel was redesigned and the Vibrancy effect was reduced in certain areas, such as Mission Control.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The system typeface was changed once more, to Apple's own San Francisco typeface, concurrent with iOS 9 and following the typeface's release in watchOS in April 2015.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] These changes continued throughout macOS Sierra, High Sierra, Mojave, and Catalina.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] macOS Big Sur brought major changes to Aqua design that brings it in line with other Apple platforms such as iOS and iPadOS.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The Dock was detached from the screen edge and more rounded on all corners.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The icons were all squircle-shaped and took on more noticeable depth in general.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Titlebars lost their gradient chrome, opting for a flat white look, and the titlebar text was now bold, and inline with toolbar items, which are no longer contained within a distinct background.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Modal dialogs had changed significantly, only being as large as the content inside; laid out with a large icon at the top, text in the center, and buttons at the bottom.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Sheets no longer slided out like paper from under the titlebar, instead more simply fading in from the center of the window.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Unified sidebars have become more commonplace and are the default for all applications.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Windows now had more rounded corners and take on a tint from the user's wallpaper, akin to Windows 11's Mica effect.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The menubar was now completely transparent, using a strong blur to differentiate from the background.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] This revision of Aqua continued to be used in macOS Monterey, Ventura, Sonoma, and Sequoia.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] As part of a larger movement to standardise the visual design language across their products, macOS adopted Liquid Glass with macOS Tahoe.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The Windows version of Safari, in version 3, included a functional Aqua look and feel that was very similar to macOS.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] As of version 4, a more Windows-like theme was employed using the standard Windows user interface controls and window border.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] QuickTime for Windows uses the same theme as seen in older versions of QuickTime for macOS, with brushed-metal windows and Aqua buttons on top.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Much of Aqua's original design resembled the translucent two-tone look of Apple's contemporary hardware.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In 2003 and 2004, Apple moved to the use of brushed aluminium in their industrial design (such as with the aluminium Apple Cinema Displays).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] This somewhat inconsistent mix of interface styles has been controversial among the Mac community.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] In the past, Apple has threatened legal action against those who make themes similar to their look and feel.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] The Mac skinning community took exception to Apple's heavy-handed actions against all Aqua lookalikes.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/aqua-user-interface] Stardock's Brad Wardell contrasted the company's litigious approach with Microsoft's approach to incorporating third-party skins into Windows XP.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Cocoa consists of the Foundation Kit, Application Kit, and Core Data frameworks, as included by the `Cocoa.h` header file, and the libraries and frameworks included by those, such as the C standard library and the Objective-C runtime.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Cocoa applications are typically developed using the development tools provided by Apple, specifically Xcode (formerly Project Builder) and Interface Builder (now part of Xcode), using the programming languages Objective-C or Swift.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] However, the Cocoa programming environment can be accessed using other tools.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] It is also possible to write Objective-C Cocoa programs in a simple text editor and build it manually with GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) or Clang from the command line or from a makefile.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] For end users, Cocoa applications are those written using the Cocoa programming environment.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Such applications usually have a familiar look and feel, since the Cocoa programming environment provides a lot of common UI elements (such as buttons, scroll bars, etc.), and automates many aspects of an application to comply with Apple's human interface guidelines.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] For iOS, iPadOS, tvOS, and watchOS, APIs similar to Application Kit, named UIKit and WatchKit, are available; they include gesture recognition, animation, and a different set of graphical control elements that are designed to accommodate the specific platforms they target.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Foundation Kit and Core Data are also available in those operating systems.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] It is used in applications for Apple devices such as the iPhone, the iPod Touch, the iPad, the Apple TV, and the Apple Watch.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Cocoa continues the lineage of several software frameworks (mainly the *App Kit* and *Foundation Kit*) from the NeXTSTEP and OpenStep programming environments developed by NeXT in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Apple acquired NeXT in December 1996, and subsequently went to work on the Rhapsody operating system that was to be the direct successor of OPENSTEP.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] It was to have had an emulation base for classic Mac OS applications, named *Blue Box*.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The OpenStep base of libraries and binary support was termed *Yellow Box*.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Rhapsody evolved into Mac OS X, and the Yellow Box became Cocoa.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Thus, Cocoa classes begin with the letters *NS*, such as NSString or NSArray.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] These stand for the original proprietary term for the OpenStep framework, NeXTSTEP.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Much of the work that went into developing OpenStep was applied to developing Mac OS X, Cocoa being the most visible part.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] For example, NeXTSTEP and OpenStep used Display PostScript for on-screen display of text and graphics, while Cocoa depends on Apple's Quartz (which uses the Portable Document Format (PDF) imaging model, but not its underlying technology).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Cocoa also has a level of World Wide Web support, including the NSURL and WebKit HTML classes, and others, while OpenStep had only rudimentary support for managed network connections via NSFileHandle classes and Berkeley sockets.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The API toolbox was originally called “Yellow Box” and was renamed to Cocoa - a name that had been already trademarked by Apple.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Apple's *Cocoa* trademark had originated as the name of a multimedia project design application for children.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The name was intended to evoke "Java for kids", as it ran embedded in web pages.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The original "Cocoa" program was discontinued following the return of Steve Jobs to Apple.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] At the time, Java was a big focus area for the company, so “Cocoa” was used as the new name for “Yellow Box” because, in addition to the native Objective-C usage, it could also be accessed from Java via a bridging layer.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Even though Apple discontinued support for the Cocoa Java bridge, the name continued and was even used for the Cocoa Touch API.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] One feature of the Cocoa environment is its facility for managing dynamically allocated memory.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Foundation Kit's NSObject class, from which most classes, both vendor and user, are derived, implements a reference counting scheme for memory management.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Objects that derive from the NSObject root class respond to a `retain` and a `release` message, and keep a retain count.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] A method titled `retainCount` exists, but contrary to its name, will usually not return the exact retain count of an object.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] It is mainly used for system-level purposes.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Invoking it manually is not recommended by Apple.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] A newly allocated object created with `alloc` or `copy` has a retain count of one.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Sending that object a `retain` message increments the retain count, while sending it a `release` message decrements the retain count.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] When an object's retain count reaches zero, it is deallocated by a procedure similar to a C++ *destructor*.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] `dealloc` is not guaranteed to be invoked.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Starting with Objective-C 2.0, the Objective-C runtime implemented an optional garbage collector, which is now obsolete and deprecated in favor of Automatic Reference Counting (ARC).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] In this model, the runtime turned Cocoa reference counting operations such as "retain" and "release" into no-ops.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The garbage collector does not exist on the iOS implementation of Objective-C 2.0.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Garbage collection in Objective-C ran on a low-priority background thread, and can halt on Cocoa's user events, with the intention of keeping the user experience responsive.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The legacy garbage collector is still available on Mac OS X version 10.13, but no Apple-provided applications use it.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] In 2011, the LLVM compiler introduced Automatic Reference Counting (ARC), which replaces the conventional garbage collector by performing static analysis of Objective-C source code and inserting retain and release messages as necessary.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Cocoa consists of three Objective-C object libraries called *frameworks*.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Frameworks are functionally similar to shared libraries, a compiled object that can be dynamically loaded into a program's address space at runtime, but frameworks add associated resources, header files, and documentation.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The Cocoa frameworks are implemented as a type of bundle, containing the aforementioned items in standard locations.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] A key part of the Cocoa architecture is its comprehensive views model.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] This is organized along conventional lines for an application framework, but is based on the Portable Document Format (PDF) drawing model provided by Quartz.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] This allows creating custom drawing content using PostScript-like drawing commands, which also allows automatic printer support and so forth.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Since the Cocoa framework manages all the clipping, scrolling, scaling and other chores of drawing graphics, the programmer is freed from implementing basic infrastructure and can concentrate on the unique aspects of an application's content.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The Smalltalk teams at Xerox PARC eventually settled on a design philosophy that led to easy development and high code reuse.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Cocoa's design is a fairly, but not absolutely strict application of MVC principles.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Under OpenStep, most of the classes provided were either high-level View classes (in AppKit) or one of a number of relatively low-level model classes like NSString.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Compared to similar MVC systems, OpenStep lacked a strong model layer.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] No stock class represented a "document," for instance.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] During the transition to Cocoa, the model layer was expanded greatly, introducing a number of pre-rolled classes to provide functionality common to desktop applications.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] In Mac OS X 10.3, Apple introduced the NSController family of classes, which provide predefined behavior for the controller layer.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] These classes are considered part of the Cocoa Bindings system, which also makes extensive use of protocols such as Key-Value Observing and Key-Value Binding.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The term 'binding' refers to a relationship between two objects, often between a view and a controller.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Bindings allow the developer to focus more on declarative relationships rather than orchestrating fine-grained behavior.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] With the arrival of Mac OS X 10.4, Apple extended this foundation further by introducing the Core Data framework, which standardizes change tracking and persistence in the model layer.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] In effect, the framework greatly simplifies the process of making changes to application data, undoing changes when necessary, saving data to disk, and reading it back in.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] In providing framework support for all three MVC domains, Apple's goal is to reduce the amount of boilerplate or "glue" code that developers have to write, freeing up resources to spend time on application-specific features.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] In most object-oriented languages, calls to methods are represented physically by a pointer to the code in memory.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] This restricts the design of an application since specific *command handling* classes are needed, usually organized according to the chain-of-responsibility pattern.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] While Cocoa retains this approach for the most part, Objective-C's late binding opens up more flexibility.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Under Objective-C, methods are represented by a *selector*, a string describing the method to call.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] When a message is sent, the selector is sent into the Objective-C runtime, matched against a list of available methods, and the method's *implementation* is called.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Since the selector is text data, this lets it be saved to a file, transmitted over a network or between processes, or manipulated in other ways.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The implementation of the method is looked up at runtime, not compile time.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] There is a small performance penalty for this, but late binding allows the same selector to reference different implementations.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] By a similar token, Cocoa provides a pervasive data manipulation method called *key-value coding* (KVC).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] This allows a piece of data or property of an object to be looked up or changed at runtime by name.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The property name acts as a key to the value.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] In traditional languages, this late binding is impossible.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] An object's type need not be known, yet any property of that object can be discovered using KVC.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Also, by extending this system using something Cocoa terms *key-value observing* (KVO), automatic support for undo-redo is provided.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Late static binding is a variant of binding somewhere between static and dynamic binding.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The binding of names before the program is run is called static (*early*); bindings performed as the program runs are dynamic (*late* or *virtual*).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] One of the most useful features of Cocoa is the powerful *base objects* the system supplies.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] As an example, consider the Foundation classes `NSString` and `NSAttributedString`, which provide Unicode strings, and the `NSText` system in AppKit, which allows the programmer to place string objects in the GUI.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] `NSText` and its related classes are used to display and edit strings.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Paragraph layout can be controlled automatically or by the user, using a built-in "ruler" object that can be attached to any text view.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Spell checking is automatic, using a system-wide set of language dictionaries.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Unlimited undo/redo support is built in.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Using only the built-in features, one can write a text editor application in as few as 10 lines of code.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] With new controller objects, this may fall towards zero.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] When extensions are needed, Cocoa's use of Objective-C makes this a straightforward task.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Objective-C includes the concept of "categories," which allows modifying existing class "in-place".
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Functionality can be accomplished in a category without any changes to the original classes in the framework, or even access to its source.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] In other common languages, this same task requires deriving a new subclass supporting the added features, and then replacing all instances of the original class with instances of the new subclass.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The Cocoa frameworks are written in Objective-C.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Cocoa's need for runtime binding means many of Cocoa's key features are not available with Java.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] In 2005, Apple announced that the Java bridge was to be deprecated, meaning that features added to Cocoa in macOS versions later than 10.4 would not be added to the Cocoa-Java programming interface.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] At Apple Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) 2014, Apple introduced a new programming language named Swift, which is intended to replace Objective-C.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Originally, AppleScript Studio could be used to develop simpler Cocoa applications.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] However, as of Snow Leopard, it has been deprecated.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] It was replaced with AppleScriptObjC, which allows programming in AppleScript, while using Cocoa frameworks.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] The Cocoa programming environment can be accessed using other tools with the aid of bridge mechanisms such as PasCocoa, PyObjC, CamelBones, RubyCocoa, and a D/Objective-C Bridge.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] Third-party bindings available for other languages include AppleScript, Clozure CL, Monobjc and NObjective (C#), Cocoa# (CLI), Cocodao and D/Objective-C Bridge, LispWorks, Object Pascal, CamelBones (Perl), PyObjC (Python), FPC PasCocoa (Lazarus and Free Pascal), RubyCocoa (Ruby).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] A Ruby language implementation named MacRuby, which removes the need for a bridge mechanism, was formerly developed by Apple, while Nu is a Lisp-like language that uses the Objective-C object model directly, and thus can use the Cocoa frameworks without needing a binding.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/cocoa-api] There are also open source implementations of major parts of the Cocoa framework, such as GNUstep and Cocotron, which allow cross-platform Cocoa application development to target other operating systems, such as Microsoft Windows and Linux.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] The **Foundation Kit**, or just **Foundation** for short, is an Objective-C framework in the OpenStep specification described by NeXT Computer, Inc.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] It provides basic classes such as wrapper classes and data structure classes.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] This framework uses the prefix NS (for NeXTSTEP).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] It is also part of Cocoa and of the Swift standard library.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] This class is the most common base class for Objective-C hierarchies and provides standard methods for working with objects by managing the memory associated with them and querying them.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] A class used for string manipulation, representing a Unicode string (most typically using UTF-16 as its internal format).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] NSString is immutable, and thus can only be initialized but not modified.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] NSMutableString is a modifiable version.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] NSValue is a wrapper class for C data types, and NSNumber is a wrapper class for C number data types such as **int**, **double**, and **float**.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] The data structures in Foundation Kit can only hold objects, not primitive types, so wrappers such as NSValue and NSNumber are used in those data structures.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] A dynamic array of objects, supporting constant-time indexing.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] NSArray is an immutable version that can only be initialized with objects but not modified.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] NSMutableArray may be modified by adding and removing objects.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] An associative data container of key-value pairs with unique keys.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] Searching and element addition and removal (in the case of NSMutableDictionary) is faster-than-linear.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] However, the order of the elements within the container is not guaranteed.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] An associative container of unique keys, similar to NSDictionary, with the difference that members do not contain a data object.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] An object of this type can dynamically allocate and manage its data, or it can refer to data owned by and managed by something else (such as a static numeric array).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] Classes that store times and dates and represent calendrical information.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] They offer methods for calculating date and time differences.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] Together with NSLocale, they provide methods for displaying dates and times in many formats, and for adjusting times and dates based on location in the world.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] The Foundation Kit is part of the macOS Cocoa API.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] Beginning as the successor to OPENSTEP/Mach, this framework has deviated from OpenStep compliance, and is in some places incompatible.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] The Foundation Kit is in the iOS Cocoa Touch API.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] This framework is based on the macOS Cocoa.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] The Foundation Kit is implemented in GNUstep's Base Package (libs-base).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] This implementation is mostly comparable (4 classes are missing) and aims to be comparable with both the OpenStep API and later macOS additions.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] The missing classes have been dropped by Apple as well.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] The Foundation Kit is implemented in Cocotron, an open-source implementation of Cocoa.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] PureFoundation is an open-source implementation of Foundation that implements Foundation by wrapping Core Foundation, just like in Cocoa, rather than create a separate Foundation from scratch like GNUstep and Cocotron.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] SwiftFoundation (swift-corelibs-foundation) is Apple's open-source Swift implementation of the Foundation API for platforms where there is no Objective-C runtime.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] It also includes an implementation of Core Foundation.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] ApportableFoundation is an implementation of Foundation Kit (Foundation, CoreFoundation, and CFNetwork) based on Apple's CFLite release.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/foundation-kit] It works on Android and other Linux systems, and makes up part of the Darling macOS translation layer for Linux.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] Interface Builder is descended from the NeXTSTEP development software of the same name.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] A version of Interface Builder is also used in the development of OpenStep software, and a very similar tool called Gorm exists for GNUstep.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] On March 27, 2008, a specialized iPhone version of Interface Builder allowing interface construction for iPhone applications was released with the iPhone SDK Beta 2.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] Interface Builder was intentionally developed as a separate application, to allow interaction designers to design interfaces without having to use a code-oriented IDE, but as of Xcode 4, Apple has integrated its functionality directly into Xcode.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] Originally the software was called *SOS Interface*, and was created by Jean-Marie Hullot whilst he was a researcher at Inria at Rocquencourt near Paris.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] He was allowed to retain ownership of the software upon resigning from Inria, and spent a year working it into a fully-featured product, now named *Interface Builder* and distributed for Macintosh by ExperTelligence in the USA in 1986.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] It was written in Lisp (for the *ExperLisp* product by *ExperTelligence*) and deeply integrated with the Macintosh Toolbox.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] *Interface Builder* was presented at MacWorld Expo in San Francisco in January 1987.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] Denison Bollay took Jean-Marie Hullot to NeXT after MacWorld Expo to demonstrate it to Steve Jobs.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] Jobs recognized its value, and started incorporating it into NeXTSTEP, and by 1988 it was part of NeXTSTEP 0.8.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] It was the first commercial application that allowed interface objects, such as buttons, menus, and windows, to be placed in an interface using a mouse.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] One notable early use of *Interface Builder* was the development of the first web browser, WorldWideWeb by Tim Berners-Lee at CERN, made using a NeXT workstation.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] Interface Builder provides *palettes*, or collections, of user interface objects to an Objective-C or Swift developer.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] These user interface objects contain items like text fields, data tables, sliders, and pop-up menus.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] Interface Builder's palettes are completely extensible, meaning any developer can develop new objects and add palettes to Interface Builder.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] To build an interface, a developer simply drags interface objects from the palette onto a window or menu.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] *Actions* (messages) which the objects can emit are connected to *targets* in the application's code and *outlets* (pointers) declared in the application's code are connected to specific objects.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] In this way all initialization is done before runtime, both improving performance and streamlining the development process.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] When Interface Builder was a standalone application, interface designers could ship nib files to developers, who would then drop them into their projects.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] Interface Builder saves an application's interface as a bundle that contains the interface objects and relationships used in the application.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] These objects are archived (a process also known as serialization or marshalling in other contexts) into either an XML file or a NeXT-style property list file with a .nib extension.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] Upon running an application, the proper NIB objects are unarchived, connected into the binary of their owning application, and awakened.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/interface-builder] As of Interface Builder version 3, a new file format (with extension .xib) has been added, which is functionally identical to .nib, except it is stored in a flat file, making it more suitable for storage in revision control systems and processing by tools such as diff.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C programs developed for non-Apple operating systems or that are not dependent on Apple's APIs may also be compiled for any platform supported by GNU, GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) or LLVM/Clang.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C source code "messaging/implementation" program files usually have `.m` filename extensions, while Objective-C "header/interface" files have `.h` extensions, the same as C header files.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C++ files are denoted with a `.mm` filename extension.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C was created mainly by Brad Cox and Tom Love in the early 1980s at their company Productivity Products International (PPI).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Leading up to the creation of their company, both had been introduced to Smalltalk while at ITT Corporation's Programming Technology Center in 1981.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The earliest work on Objective-C traces back to around then.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Cox was intrigued by problems of true reusability in software design and programming.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] He realized that a language like Smalltalk would be invaluable in building development environments for system developers at ITT.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] However, he and Tom Love also recognized that backward compatibility with C was critically important in ITT's telecom engineering milieu.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Cox began writing a pre-processor for C to add some of the abilities of Smalltalk.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] He soon had a working implementation of an object-oriented extension to the C language, which he named Object-Oriented Pre-Compiler (OOPC).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Love was hired by Schlumberger Research in 1982 and had the opportunity to acquire the first commercial copy of Smalltalk-80, which further influenced the development of their brainchild.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] To demonstrate that real progress could be made, Cox showed that making interchangeable software components really needed only a few practical changes to existing tools.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Specifically, they needed to support objects in a flexible manner, come supplied with a usable set of libraries, and allow for the code (and any resources needed by the code) to be bundled into one cross-platform format.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Love and Cox eventually formed PPI to commercialize their product.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] To avoid legal disputes with his previous employers, Cox reimplemented his compiler for the language, which was renamed "Objective-C".
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The company's main product line consisted of this compiler, along with class libraries intended to be used with it.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In 1986, Cox published the main description of Objective-C in its original form in the book *Object-Oriented Programming: An Evolutionary Approach*.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Although he was careful to explain that there is more to the problem of reusability than just what Objective-C provides, the language was often compared feature for feature with other languages.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In 1988, NeXT licensed Objective-C from StepStone (the new name of PPI, the owner of the Objective-C trademark) and extended the GCC compiler to support Objective-C.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] NeXT developed the Application Kit (AppKit) and Foundation Kit libraries on which the NeXTSTEP user interface and Interface Builder were based.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] While the NeXT workstations failed to make a great impact in the marketplace, the tools were widely lauded in the industry.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] NeXT dropped hardware production and focused on software tools, selling NeXTSTEP (and OPENSTEP) as a platform for custom programming.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] To circumvent the terms of the GPL, NeXT had originally intended to ship the Objective-C frontend separately, allowing the user to link it with GCC to produce the compiler executable.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Stallman, this plan was rejected after Stallman consulted with GNU's lawyers and NeXT agreed to make Objective-C part of GCC.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The work to extend GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) was led by Steve Naroff, who joined NeXT from StepStone.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The compiler changes were made available as per GNU General Public License (GPL) terms, but the runtime libraries were not, rendering the open source contribution unusable to the general public.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] This led to other parties developing such runtime libraries under open source licenses.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Later, Steve Naroff was also principal contributor to work at Apple to build the Objective-C frontend to Clang.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The GNU project started work on its free software implementation of Cocoa, named GNUstep, based on the OpenStep standard.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Dennis Glatting wrote the first GNU Objective-C runtime in 1992.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The current GNU Objective-C runtime, in use since 1993, is the one developed by Kresten Krab Thorup while he was a university student in Denmark.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Thorup also worked at NeXT from 1993 to 1996.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] After acquiring NeXT in 1996, Apple Computer used OpenStep in its then-new operating system, Mac OS X.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] This included Objective-C, NeXT's Objective-C-based developer tool, Project Builder, and its interface design tool, Interface Builder.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Both were later merged into one application, Xcode.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Most of Apple's current Cocoa API is based on OpenStep interface objects and is the most significant Objective-C environment being used for active development.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] At Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) 2014, Apple introduced a new language, Swift, which was characterized as "Objective-C without the C".
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C is a thin layer atop C and is a "strict superset" of C, meaning that it is possible to compile any C program with an Objective-C compiler and to freely include C language code within an Objective-C class.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C derives its object syntax from Smalltalk.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] All of the syntax for non-object-oriented operations (including primitive variables, pre-processing, expressions, function declarations, and function calls) are identical to those of C, while the syntax for object-oriented features is an implementation of Smalltalk-style messaging.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The Objective-C model of object-oriented programming is based on message passing to object instances.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In Objective-C, one does not *call a method*; one *sends a message*.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] This is unlike the Simula-style programming model used by C++.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The difference between these two concepts is in how the code referenced by the method or message name is executed.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In a Simula-style language, the method name is—in most cases—bound to a section of code in the target class by the compiler.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In Smalltalk and Objective-C, the target of a message is resolved at runtime, with the receiving object itself interpreting the message.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] A method is identified by a *selector* or `SEL` — a unique identifier for each message name, often just a `NUL`-terminated string representing its name—and resolved to a C method pointer implementing it: an `IMP`.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] A consequence of this is that the message-passing system has no type checking.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The object to which the message is directed—the *receiver*—is not guaranteed to respond to a message, and if it does not, it raises an exception.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The "method" call is translated by the compiler to the `objc_msgSend(id self, SEL op, ...)` family of runtime functions.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Different implementations handle modern additions like `super`.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In GNU families, this function is named `objc_msg_sendv`, but it has been deprecated in favor of a modern lookup system under `objc_msg_lookup`.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Both styles of programming have multiple strengths and weaknesses.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Object-oriented programming in the Simula (C++) style allows multiple inheritance and faster execution by using compile-time binding whenever possible, but it does not support dynamic binding by default.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] It also forces all methods to have a corresponding implementation unless they are abstract.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The Smalltalk-style programming as used in Objective-C allows messages to go unimplemented, with the method resolved to its implementation at runtime.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] For example, a message may be sent to a collection of objects, to which only some will be expected to respond, without fear of producing runtime errors.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Message passing also does not require that an object be defined at compile time.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] An implementation is still required for the method to be called in the derived object.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C requires that the interface and implementation of a class be in separately declared code blocks.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] By convention, developers place the interface in a header file and the implementation in a code file.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The header files, normally suffixed .h, are similar to C header files while the implementation (method) files, normally suffixed .m, can be very similar to C code files.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] This is analogous to class declarations as used in other object-oriented languages, such as C++ or Python.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The interface of a class is usually defined in a header file.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] A common convention is to name the header file after the name of the class, e.g.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] `Ball.h` would contain the interface for the class `Ball`.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In the above, plus signs denote class methods, or methods that can be called on the class itself (not on an instance), and minus signs denote instance methods, which can only be called on a particular instance of the class.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Class methods also have no access to instance variables.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Note that `instanceMethod2With2Parameters:param2_callName:` demonstrates the interleaving of selector segments with argument expressions, for which there is no direct equivalent in C/C++.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Return types can be any standard C type, a pointer to a generic Objective-C object, a pointer to a specific type of object such as NSArray *, NSImage *, or NSString *, or a pointer to the class to which the method belongs (instancetype).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The default return type is the generic Objective-C type `id`.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Method arguments begin with a name labeling the argument that is part of the method name, followed by a colon followed by the expected argument type in parentheses and the argument name.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] A derivative of the interface definition is the *category*, which allows one to add methods to existing classes.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The interface only declares the class interface and not the methods themselves: the actual code is written in the implementation file.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Implementation (method) files normally have the file extension `.m`, which originally signified "messages".
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Methods are written using their interface declarations.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The syntax allows pseudo-naming of arguments.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Internal representations of a method vary between different implementations of Objective-C.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] If myColor is of the class `Color`, instance method `-changeColorToRed:green:blue:` might be internally labeled `_i_Color_changeColorToRed_green_blue`.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The `i` is to refer to an instance method, with the class and then method names appended and colons changed to underscores.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] As the order of parameters is part of the method name, it cannot be changed to suit coding style or expression as with true named parameters.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] However, internal names of the function are rarely used directly.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Generally, messages are converted to function calls defined in the Objective-C runtime library.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] It is not necessarily known at link time which method will be called because the class of the receiver (the object being sent the message) need not be known until runtime.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Once an Objective-C class is written, it can be instantiated.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] This is done by first allocating an uninitialized instance of the class (an object) and then by initializing it.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] An object is not fully functional until both steps have been completed.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] These steps should be accomplished with one line of code so that there is never an allocated object that hasn't undergone initialization (and because it is unwise to keep the intermediate result since `-init` can return a different object than that on which it is called).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Also, some classes implement class method initializers.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Like `+new`, they combine `+alloc` and `-init`, but unlike `+new`, they return an autoreleased instance.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The *alloc* message allocates enough memory to hold all the instance variables for an object, sets all the instance variables to zero values, and turns the memory into an instance of the class; at no point during the initialization is the memory an instance of the superclass.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The *init* message performs the set-up of the instance upon creation.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In the above example, notice the `id` return type.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] This type stands for *pointer to any object* in Objective-C (See the Dynamic typing section).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The initializer pattern is used to assure that the object is properly initialized by its superclass before the init method performs its initialization.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] A non-valid object pointer has the value `nil`; conditional statements like `if` treat nil like a null pointer, so the initialization code will not be executed if `[super init]` returned nil.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] If there is an error in initialization, the init method should perform any necessary cleanup, including sending a `release` message to self, and return `nil` to indicate that initialization failed.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Any checking for such errors must only be performed after having called the superclass initialization to ensure that destroying the object will be done correctly.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] If a class has more than one initialization method, only one of them (the *designated initializer*) needs to follow this pattern; others should call the designated initializer instead of the superclass initializer.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In other programming languages, these are called *interfaces*.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C was extended at NeXT to introduce the concept of multiple inheritance of specification, but not implementation, through the introduction of protocols.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] This is a pattern achievable either as an abstract multiple inherited base class in C++, or as an *interface* (as in Java and C#).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C makes use of ad hoc protocols called *informal protocols* and compiler-enforced protocols called *formal protocols*.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] An informal protocol is a list of methods that a class can opt to implement.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] It is specified in the documentation, since it has no presence in the language.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Informal protocols are implemented as a category (see below) on NSObject and often include optional methods, which, if implemented, can change the behavior of a class.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] For example, a text field class might have a delegate that implements an informal protocol with an optional method for performing auto-completion of user-typed text.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The text field discovers whether the delegate implements that method (via reflective programming (reflection)) and, if so, calls the delegate's method to support the auto-complete feature.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] A formal protocol is similar to an interface in Java, C#, and Ada 2005.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] It is a list of methods that any class can declare itself to implement.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C versions before 2.0 required that a class must implement all methods in a protocol it declares itself as adopting; the compiler will emit an error if the class does not implement every method from its declared protocols.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C 2.0 added support for marking certain methods in a protocol optional, and the compiler will not enforce implementation of optional methods.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] A class must be declared to implement that protocol to be said to conform to it.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Formal protocols cannot provide any implementations; they simply assure callers that classes that conform to the protocol will provide implementations.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In the NeXT/Apple library, protocols are frequently used by the Distributed Objects system to represent the abilities of an object executing on a remote system.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] denotes that there is the abstract idea of locking.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] instances of NSLock claim that they will provide an implementation for the two instance methods.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C, like Smalltalk, can use dynamic typing: an object can be sent a message that is not specified in its interface.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] This can allow for increased flexibility, as it allows an object to "capture" a message and send the message to a different object that can respond to the message appropriately, or likewise send the message on to another object.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] This behavior is known as *message forwarding* or *delegation* (see below).
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Alternatively, an error handler can be used in case the message cannot be forwarded.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] If an object does not forward a message, respond to it, or handle an error, then the system will generate a runtime exception.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] If messages are sent to *nil* (the null object pointer), they will be silently ignored or raise a generic exception, depending on compiler options.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Static typing information may also optionally be added to variables.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] This information is then checked at compile time.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In the following four statements, increasingly specific type information is provided.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The statements are equivalent at runtime, but the extra information allows the compiler to warn the programmer if the passed argument does not match the type specified.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* may be of any class.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* may be an instance of any class that conforms to the *`NSCopying`* protocol.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* must be an instance of the *NSNumber* class.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* must be an instance of the *NSNumber* class, and it must conform to the *`NSCopying`* protocol.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] In Objective-C, all objects are represented as pointers, and static initialization is not allowed.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The simplest object is the type that id (objc_obj *) points to, which only has an *isa* pointer describing its class.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Other types from C, like values and structs, are unchanged because they are not part of the object system.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] This decision differs from the C++ object model, where structs and classes are united.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Objective-C permits the sending of a message to an object that may not respond.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Rather than responding or simply dropping the message, an object can forward the message to an object that can respond.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Forwarding can be used to simplify implementation of certain design patterns, such as the observer pattern or the proxy pattern.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] An object wishing to implement forwarding needs only to override the forwarding method with a new method to define the forwarding behavior.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The action method `performv::` need not be overridden, as this method merely performs an action based on the selector and arguments.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Notice the `SEL` type, which is the type of messages in Objective-C.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Note: in OpenStep, Cocoa, and GNUstep, the commonly used frameworks of Objective-C, one does not use the `Object` class.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] The `- (void)forwardInvocation:(NSInvocation *)anInvocation` method of the `NSObject` class is used to do forwarding.
[src:cocoa-appkit-deep/objective-c] Here is an example of a program that demonstrates the basics of forwarding.
